<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10450&amp;p=117495#p117495"><![CDATA[
Best to just google. I'm in an AAS class for Electronics, so I'm getting to some of thoe, but understand most.<br /><br />Sinking current is taking it from somewhere, sourcing it is basically giving it out. If a device is connected to an IC, like an LED, it sinks current, from the source, the IC.<br /><br />Some other stuff is just talking about mA numbers for I/O range, sinks and sources. Some seem to be about fluctuation in temperature.<br /><br />Lastly, how much current is needed depends on the devices used. Just add them all up. An NES in whole takes up about 350 mA of current, more with more complex mappers. An LED takes 15mA of current to run alone. Other IC's will take some of the voltage/current to run on, too. It just all adds up, it's not too bad.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4311">3gengames</a> — Mon Sep 02, 2013 10:20 pm</p><hr />
