<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10450&amp;p=117480#p117480"><![CDATA[
Only read the first part...but imagine, water in a pipe. The SNES uses so much water (The current). Voltage is basically, the pipe being sucked on by a vacuum to bring it through the pipe. Resistance...well, not good with this example, but imagine it like a sponge in the pipe, it just makes it harder for the water to go through. But current is basically the &quot;flow&quot; that really allows logic levels to switch, to detect highs and lows, etc. it's mA because it's being measured in thousandths of Amps, as 1 amp is a lot of water (electron) flow. I hope you're familiar with Kilo, Mega, Giga, and then the inverses, Milli, Micro, Nano, Pico, etc. I hope that helps some.<br /><br />ETA: Also, you usually what are called &quot;CLR's&quot; or Current Limiting Resistors. Basically, you use the CLR on the output to control how much current the chip allows to flow through it to the device, weather it be an LED, another chip, etc.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4311">3gengames</a> — Mon Sep 02, 2013 9:05 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
